<h3>Principle</h3>

<p>
We build upon, and improved, a combinatorial (sequential) single-molecule 
fluorescence in-site hybridization (smFISH) approach. Our proprietary 
transcript-specific probes are designed to color-code targeted genes 
of interest in several rounds of hybridization and 3D-imaging (z-stacks) 
with a unique encoding scheme.
</p>

<p>
Other key features are reliable detection of very rare transcripts, 
exquisite resolution, and the possibility to post-procress 
the sample, e.g. using standard cell labeling with antibodies or dyes, 
which make the genexyz system play in a league of its own.
</p>

<h3>Workflow</h3>

<p>
Our procedure is versatile, and was succesfully applied to different cell-culture systems 
and various tissues from different organisms. 
</p>

<h4>Fixation & Hybridization</h4>

<p>
The first step is the fixation of the sample (tissues or cell cultures) to a special glass slide 
followed by the hybridization of gene-specific probes. 
We offer standard gene panels for certain applications, but also provide an online interface 
for fully customized panels to exactly match your research needs.
</p>

%# <image 1>

<h4>Imaging</h4>

<p>
Multiple rounds of coloring, imaging, and decoloring of the probes are performed. 
This process will be fully automized by our genexyz platform. 
Microscopic data capture and subsequent image analysis occurs on-the-fly. 
</p>

<h4>Results</h4>

<p>
The final output are segmented spots with corresponding gene identity in an easy 
to process plain text file. Intersections with regions of interest such as 
cell-boundaries or other spacial domains yield data in formats compatible with 
standard downstream bioinformatic tools commonly applied to characterize and 
cluster single cells based on transcription profiles.
</p>

